reels.transcript: This person from Bengaluru, Pankaj Tambar, just turned his helmet into a traffic police device with AI agents that detect road violations, attach proofs with location and number plates and send it straight to police. At its core, the system basically uses a forward-facing camera that continuously captures road footage, identifies vehicles in near real-time using something like YOLO, an object detection model, and flags violations like missing helmets, wrong side driving or stunts. Once detected, the system extracts number plates using OCR, attaches location and timestamps and sends the entire incident to Bengaluru Traffic Police. What's interesting is how portable the setup is. The entire system runs on a Raspberry Pi 4B connected to a camera, a GPS module and a power bank using USB, while the internet comes through the phone's hotspot. Currently leading the back-end team at Inmobi, the second-floor guy has also confirmed that Bengaluru City Police have already contacted him, suggesting that authorities might actually be interested in the prototype.

reels.captionHook: Google now allows you to verify if a video is AI-generated right inside the Gemini app!
reels.spokenHook: Google now allows you to verify if a video is AI generated right inside the Gemini app. Here's how to do it. You simply open the Gemini app, upload a video, and ask if it's AI generated and that's it.
reels.transcript: Google now allows you to verify if a video is AI generated right inside the Gemini app. Here's how to do it. You simply open the Gemini app, upload a video, and ask if it's AI generated and that's it. At the center of this is SynthID. Think of it as an invisible pattern that Google embeds into every video it generates. It is not a visible watermark that you can strip out. Instead, it lives inside the video itself, baked into the pixels and motion. And because of that, it survives most compression, resizing, and edits. Having said that, it only works with videos generated by Veo, since SynthID isn't universally adopted yet. But verification is only one part of the update. Google also rolled out Veo 3.1, which now supports native vertical video with a more expressive model, which is better at keeping characters, objects, and backgrounds consistent. The third major change is quality. Across all Veo models, you can now upscale videos to 1080p and even 4K, which is useful for professional video editors. Overall, these updates show that Google is pushing both sides forward at once, making it easier to generate ultra-realistic videos while also making it easier to detect them.

reels.transcript: Apple and Google have just come together to finally fix Siri. That's right, Apple and Google have just entered a multi-year deal under which the next generation of Apple Foundation models powering Apple Intelligence and Siri will now be using Google Gemini. Now, this is not the first time Apple has tried to fix things by partnering with someone else. Back in 2024, Apple integrated ChatGPT to its system, but that was never meant to fix Apple Intelligence or Siri. ChatGPT was just an extra tool for things like writing, summaries or answering open-ended questions. Simply put, Siri itself was not running on ChatGPT, it was simply delegating to ChatGPT. So the core issue remained the same, Siri still felt useless beyond setting alarms. But this new deal with Google is different in a very real way. This time, Apple is not just handing hard queries to another tool, but building Apple Intelligence and Siri on top of Gemini itself. This also does not mean Apple is handing user data to Google. Both have clearly mentioned that Apple Intelligence and Siri will still run on-device or fall back to Apple's own private cloud compute when needed, meaning Apple will still control what data is seen. Having said that, the new Siri will likely be demoed at WWDC in June 2026. So let's see what Apple cooks this time.

reels.captionHook: Researchers just created a drug that increases your sleep quality by 90% without making you sleep longer!
reels.spokenHook: Researchers just created a drug that increases your sleep quality by 90% without making you sleep longer. It's called BMB-101.
reels.transcript: Researchers just created a drug that increases your sleep quality by 90% without making you sleep longer. It's called BMB-101. And to understand how it works, you need to understand a small region in your brain called the locus coeruleus. Think of it as the brain's stay-awake switch. When it is firing, your brain stays alert and actively resists REM sleep, a major contributor to sleep quality. But once BMB-101 enters your system, it targets that switch directly. It acts on a serotonin receptor called 5-HT1A, which gently lowers activity in the locus coeruleus, helping your brain increase just the REM sleep. And the results show. In phase 2 clinical trials, as released by Bright Minds Biosciences, REM increased from just 56 minutes to nearly 107 minutes per night, a 90% jump. As for side effects, they seem relatively low so far, like mild fatigue, headaches or constipation. Overall, BMB-101 points to a completely different way of treating sleep disorders. And if future trials confirm these results, this could drastically change our collective well-being.

reels.transcript: Get ready for the biggest shift in work since the internet. By 2026, AI won't just be a tool you command, it will be a teammate you collaborate with. It's being embedded across Microsoft 365, Teams, Windows, and Edge. It will be able to join meetings on your behalf, summarize discussions, and even draft responses. Imagine a 7-person team scaling to the output of a 70-person team. That's the power of these AI agents. Handling everything from meeting minutes to in-depth analysis, boosting productivity exponentially. And it's not just Microsoft. OpenAI is pushing the boundaries with its API for agents, paving the way for even more advanced agentic systems. These agents are set to accelerate research and complex problem-solving, like in the biological sciences, showcasing AI's incredible potential to tackle some of the world's biggest challenges. Google is also in the race, integrating AI across Search, Workspace, and more. Your browsing, coding, and document creation are all becoming smarter and more automated. Notions 3.0 Agent is another game-changer. Automating the busy work that consumes your day, and allowing your team to collaborate more effectively. This agent can search across all your pages, messages, and even the web, creating the ultimate knowledge base for your company. top_captions.fullCaption:
Back in 2010, Google responded to critics who claimed its Chrome browser was not fast enough with one of the most unconventional technology demonstrations ever created.

Instead of relying on bold claims or technical jargon, Google recorded real web page loads at extremely high frame rates. Chrome loading pages was shown in sync with dramatic real-world comparisons, such as a potato being fired from a cannon, alongside sound and lightning tests, to visually demonstrate how quickly the browser rendered content.

These demonstrations were not created using CGI. Every test was captured using high-speed cameras and measured against actual rendering times, making the results tangible and easy for anyone to understand.

Rather than debating performance charts and benchmarks, Google transformed browser speed into a real-world experience. This creative approach gave Chrome a memorable and lasting moment during the browser wars of the early internet era.
